delta Q.

02:29:17.620 --> 02:29:18.900
How to understand?

02:29:20.200 --> 02:29:22.560
Let’s say, you have already

02:29:22.560 --> 02:29:25.200
produced a few units.

02:29:26.720 --> 02:29:31.200
You want to produce another

02:29:31.200 --> 02:29:34.080
additional product.

02:29:36.100 --> 02:29:39.100
Another additional product.

02:29:39.600 --> 02:29:42.620
To produce an additional unit

02:29:42.620 --> 02:29:45.620
of products, additional costs

02:29:45.620 --> 02:29:48.000
must be incurred.

02:29:48.320 --> 02:29:51.600
These additional costs, which

02:29:51.880 --> 02:29:53.860
will be required by the production

02:29:53.860 --> 02:29:56.300
of an additional unit of product,

02:29:56.860 --> 02:30:00.520
are the limit costs.

02:30:00.780 --> 02:30:02.880
But look when we increase

02:30:02.880 --> 02:30:04.040
the issue?

02:30:06.520 --> 02:30:09.120
When will the total cost increase?

02:30:09.120 --> 02:30:13.280
The total costs are consisting

02:30:13.280 --> 02:30:15.680
of fixed and variable costs.

02:30:16.220 --> 02:30:19.740
Only variable costs increase.

02:30:19.900 --> 02:30:22.360
Fixed costs are not changed over

02:30:22.360 --> 02:30:26.060
a short period of time.

02:30:27.780 --> 02:30:31.520
The increase in total costs is

02:30:31.520 --> 02:30:36.660
equal to the increase in variable costs.

02:30:37.080 --> 02:30:39.920
Thus, the limit costs can be calculated

02:30:39.920 --> 02:30:43.480
by dividing the delta of the growth

02:30:43.480 --> 02:30:45.600
of variable costs, divided by the

02:30:45.900 --> 02:30:48.020
